def: Wrapped up within a leaf or sheath.

A substance resembling dextrin, obtained from the bulbs of thedahlia, the artichoke, and other sources, as a colorless, spongy,amorphous material. It is so called because by decomposition ityields levulose. [Written also l√¶vulin.]
Pertaining to, or derived from, the mesoderm; as, mesodermaltissues.
An interpreter. See Dragoman. [Obs.]And after, by the tongue, Her truchman, she reports the mind's eachthrow. B. Jonson.
The quality of being half; incompleteness. [R.]As soon as there is any departure from simplicity, and attempt athalfness, or good for me that is not good for him, my neighbor feelsthe wrong. Emerson.
In an abusive manner; rudely; with abusive language.
An imaginary monster, or hideous giant of fairy tales, wholived on human beings; hence, any frightful giant; a cruel monster.His schoolroom must have resembled an ogre's den. Maccaulay.
A minute soft filamentary process springing from the surface ofcertain hydroids and sponges.
